{"type":"FeatureCollection","source":"USGS \u2014 San Andreas & Bay Area Faults (2006)","features":[{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"Calaveras","description":"Like the San Andreas, the Calaveras fault is a strike-slip fault with right-lateral movement. The Calaveras branches off from the San Andreas just to the south of the city of Hollister. The fault is slipping continually causing curbsides and roads to be warped, as it can be observed in Hollister, but it is also saving part of its movement for a sudden slip that could cause an earthquake, particularly the northern segment in the San Ramon Valley. For more information: Calaveras Fault"},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-122.006522,37.816716],[-121.981406,37.781963],[-121.948949,37.736702],[-121.927283,37.69049],[-121.899119,37.640541],[-121.878018,37.610753],[-121.862363,37.576587],[-121.851226,37.536334],[-121.837852,37.521575],[-121.827021,37.502364],[-121.818629,37.481],[-121.808675,37.454798],[-121.784417,37.423128],[-121.757917,37.397244],[-121.72239,37.357864],[-121.704281,37.319429],[-121.67986,37.283647],[-121.663648,37.245888],[-121.632149,37.205978],[-121.595623,37.160755],[-121.567857,37.139133],[-121.552743,37.114969],[-121.524077,37.071476],[-121.510571,37.046649],[-121.482999,37.011255],[-121.471248,36.989401],[-121.455009,36.953476],[-121.440501,36.931979],[-121.426357,36.892116],[-121.414786,36.866145],[-121.391068,36.832052],[-121.360906,36.790988],[-121.334099,36.764147],[-121.298465,36.729712],[-121.270187,36.712658],[-121.256508,36.694691],[-121.224744,36.665254],[-121.184389,36.626356],[-121.140758,36.587854]]]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"Concord\u2013Green Valley","description":"Slip on the Calaveras fault to the south steps over to the Concord-Green Valley in the city of Concord, where evidence of fault creep can be seen. The fault passes 10 miles east of Napa."},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-121.991139,37.902332],[-122.002683,37.919907],[-122.008757,37.934604],[-122.016833,37.949129],[-122.031978,37.965955],[-122.045958,37.98553],[-122.074145,38.030597],[-122.088158,38.054528],[-122.103552,38.089459],[-122.120435,38.12663],[-122.132942,38.153798],[-122.140719,38.175723],[-122.150665,38.197357],[-122.158232,38.223701],[-122.163108,38.236404],[-122.162599,38.250666],[-122.165994,38.26986],[-122.173605,38.29473],[-122.180459,38.314299],[-122.184483,38.326491],[-122.198039,38.344545],[-122.198971,38.360045]]]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"Greenville","description":"The source of the 1980 Livermore Earthquake (magnitude 5.8) and minor earthquakes since, the Greenville fault includes several active segments along its 70km trace. It is a strike-slip fault with right-lateral movement. For more information: Greenville Fault"},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-121.947339,37.976676],[-121.912911,37.941739],[-121.87371,37.914297],[-121.850871,37.87921],[-121.817821,37.850499],[-121.796081,37.831769],[-121.778364,37.796027],[-121.730014,37.75415],[-121.703825,37.721787],[-121.673166,37.689989],[-121.647131,37.655303],[-121.621462,37.62515],[-121.596288,37.594472],[-121.575929,37.559054],[-121.562,37.53839],[-121.544164,37.518226],[-121.532717,37.492664],[-121.51629,37.450787],[-121.503348,37.406175],[-121.494413,37.384415],[-121.478293,37.355323]]]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"Hayward","description":"The Hayward fault is a major branch of the San Andreas fault system. Like the San Andreas, it is a right-lateral strike-slip fault. The Hayward fault is considered the most hazardous in the Bay Area, because it bisects the densely populated East Bay. The most recent large earthquake (magnitude approx. 7) occurred on the Hayward fault in 1868. For more information: Hayward Fault"},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-122.365554,38.003109],[-122.352764,37.98681],[-122.334446,37.965945],[-122.316706,37.949513],[-122.299043,37.933285],[-122.277959,37.906623],[-122.255137,37.878075],[-122.235826,37.854848],[-122.21835,37.836743],[-122.200273,37.81342],[-122.184738,37.792007],[-122.165655,37.771861],[-122.143851,37.748317],[-122.129297,37.732526],[-122.120293,37.717792],[-122.113533,37.705517],[-122.100628,37.69066],[-122.078173,37.66805],[-122.054166,37.64381],[-122.033005,37.624344],[-122.015405,37.607606],[-121.998294,37.589807],[-121.98221,37.569979],[-121.966856,37.550375],[-121.947055,37.527788],[-121.931089,37.511636],[-121.919513,37.496616],[-121.907913,37.484306]]]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"Mt. Diablo","description":"Unlike the other faults within the Bay Area, the Mt. Diablo fault does not break the Earth's surface. Rather it is a blind thrust-fault, where the rocks to the southwest are forced over the rocks to the northeast of the fault line. The fault acts essentially as a ramp, and movement upward along the fault is expressed at the surface as folding rather than fault rupture. For more information: Mt. Diablo Fault"},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-121.775877,37.736595],[-121.963168,37.832516],[-122.044785,37.891805]]]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"Rodgers Creek","description":"The northern continuation of the Hayward fault, the Rodgers Creek fault extends from San Pablo Bay through Santa Rosa. Like the Hayward fault, the Rodgers Creek is one of the most active in the Bay Area, with the highest probability of rupture in the next 30 years. For more information: Rodgers Creek Fault"},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-122.806645,38.5963],[-122.786338,38.570617],[-122.766788,38.532428],[-122.74644,38.509041],[-122.72458,38.484017],[-122.714891,38.466511],[-122.695517,38.442068],[-122.670508,38.40783],[-122.653664,38.389458],[-122.630685,38.356323],[-122.613084,38.334385],[-122.587156,38.306235],[-122.560167,38.286481],[-122.539345,38.27094],[-122.520647,38.246384],[-122.497625,38.220584],[-122.480317,38.205015],[-122.468564,38.188246],[-122.437873,38.164392]]]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fault":"San Andreas","description":"The San Andreas, a right-lateral strike-slip fault, is the main fault of the California coastal region and marks a transform boundary between the Pacific Plate and the North American Plate. It consists of a complex zone of crushed and broken rock from a few hundred feet to a mile wide that spans a length of roughly 800 miles (1287 km) along California and reaches a depth of at least 10 miles. When viewed from the ground the features that characterize it can be subtle. When viewed fom the air however, the linear arrangement of lakes, bays, and valleys along it is striking. The entire length of the northern San Andreas fault, about 296 miles, moved in 1906. For more information: San Andreas Fault"},"geometry":{"type":"MultiLineString","coordinates":[[[-124.3531,40.2428],[-124.2648,40.1834],[-124.1835,40.1195],[-124.112,40.0485],[-124.051,39.9723],[-124.0126,39.8882],[-123.9931,39.7996],[-123.978,39.7105],[-123.964515,39.619372],[-123.957329,39.553005],[-123.937833,39.497151],[-123.902596,39.397823],[-123.871719,39.342216],[-123.853737,39.287609],[-123.83713,39.235066],[-123.805054,39.176109],[-123.793785,39.1423],[-123.754433,39.090672],[-123.73214,39.055023],[-123.702599,39.016144],[-123.665092,38.967785],[-123.615227,38.915077],[-123.552635,38.840542],[-123.502449,38.788109],[-123.466141,38.750008],[-123.427948,38.710945],[-123.384712,38.666691],[-123.331978,38.615109],[-123.259377,38.542114],[-123.140373,38.430092],[-123.090012,38.380886],[-123.062698,38.34721],[-123.010017,38.281391],[-122.970367,38.235493],[-122.930298,38.193604],[-122.891335,38.151169],[-122.836151,38.090473],[-122.795265,38.040607],[-122.750305,37.99107],[-122.719955,37.960575],[-122.664253,37.896626],[-122.630257,37.860317],[-122.602547,37.826504],[-122.581223,37.79388],[-122.555519,37.750496],[-122.5224,37.708344],[-122.466232,37.646332],[-122.434242,37.609184],[-122.400246,37.56